{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, the speaker most explicitly names his condition in the opening lines, where he \"must...tread paths of exile,\" an involuntary state imposed by *wyrd* (fate), which he has decided to bear with stoic restraint and wisdom, ultimately seeking solace in heavenly grace rather than earthly comforts.[^1][^2]\n\nIn *The Seafarer*, the controlling image of exile appears in the account of past suffering, where the speaker \"wintered on paths of exile, bereft of kinsmen,\" but he has embraced it as a voluntary spiritual discipline superior to settled life on land, prioritizing \"the joys of the Lord\" over transient earthly existence.[^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [p-9cca5e](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [p-5bdc65](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 5 (*The Seafarer*), [p-889339](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-889339).\n\n[^4]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 5 (*The Seafarer*), [p-eff626](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-eff626).",
